<br>
From the direction of the Frontier Mountains, the small group could be seen.  Likely only one hundred humanoids coming through.  Teir'dal, Ogres, Trolls and humans made up the bulk of the group.  A rare gnome or Iksar scattered in.<br>
<br>
Near the front of the group, along with the platemail clad knights and warriors and robed necromancers that lead the group, one robed figure stood out.  His stark white long hair rolled behind his head and over his shoulders.  Deep dark purple chainmail armor covered his form, the enchanted adamantite not having lost it's power with the loss of the gods.  A staff of condensed black energy crackled in his hands, waiting to strike out at something to deliver it's deadly blow and let the enemy feel its' dark power.<br>
<br>
What stood out about this elf most though, was his smoke grey skin and infuriated, hateful, yet vibrant green eyes.  A strong love had died before those eyes in the past, not long after the loss of the gods, and that dead love was replaced by an infuriated hatred for those that killed that love.  The Koada'dal.<br>
<br>
Undeen Lar'Tese couldn't help but snarl, thinking about those elves, his vampiric fangs showing slightly.  He was in a mood to kill.  Which was good, for the group was marching to the Firiona Vie docks to deliver that death he sought so much.  That burning hatred had only seemed to fuel his Wizardry magics, his magical flames hotter, and his ice colder.<br>
<br>
Just over the horizon it could be seen.  A group of elves and some short race (who could tell which from so far away?) were waiting for the marching group, in hopes to protect the docks.  If this group had any word in it, those docks wouldn't be protected by anything, let alone such a weak foe.<br>
<br>
A sudden patter of many feet could be heard.  Undeen and those he marched with thought it was the enemy before them.  Across the field, the elves heard the rushing as well, and prepared to fight, thinking it the oncoming Teir'dal, humans, Ogres and Trolls.  This fight would be a bloody one.<br>
<br>
So, it was of great surprise to both sides when they found themselves flanked by hundreds upon hundreds of rushing, fanatical, suicidal Iksar.  The Iksar cared not how many of them died.  What mattered, was the death of their enemies.  These others would all be removed from THEIR Kunark.  And soon after, Norrath as a whole.  They would please their god and bring his return, even if it meant the death of every last one of them.<br>
<br>
Monk after Iksar Monk could be seen, heard, and felt, leaping into the air, jump kicking their foe to begin the fight, warriors and knights not far behind.  Last, behind them, shaman and necromancers could barely be seen through the rush, casting spells, the shaman using what feeble powers left to them with the spirits to aid the death of their foes.<br>
<br>
Undeen saw a monk leap at him in an attempt to kick him to the ground and kill him there, but the wizard would have none of it.  Planting one end of his staff into the ground for support, the grass around sizzling and dieing, Undeen caught the Iksar in the chest with the other end and not only speared the monk upon it, but used it like a pole vault, and threw the dieing Iksar over himself, preparing to fight the next foe.<br>
<br>
with a quick spell, Undeen found himself behind his charge of men, seeing them fighting, and dieing, at the hands of this unexpected foe.  Ogres could be seen, lifting Iksar in only one hand, hurling them about like rag dolls, but still, as the flood of scale came on, the Ogres even were finding themselves outnumbered, beginning to find too little room to swing an arm effectively.  This would have to be dealt with.<br>
<br>
Anger seething in his voice, Undeen began his spell, the ground out among the thick of the Iksar beginning to feel it.  Soon, all of them would.  Oh yes.  Nothing would stop him from this revenge upon the elves.  Not one Iksar, not one hundred!<br>
<br>
With a sudden rush, a chunk of the Iksar wave was thrust into the air, higher and higher, many an Iksar spinning and tumbling uncontrollably as the fell into the sky.  Soon, the hole that had once been the floating Iksar, was filled.  Perfect.  The spell lost it's effect.  Suddenly, those Iksar that had moments ago been falling into the sky, were splattering against the earth, and the Iksar that had moved to fill in their gap.<br>
<br>
At least a hundred Iksar died on impact, either landing wrong, or landed ON wrong.  Many more were injured.  Some worse then others.  But this could only help so much against the wave.  With each precious second, more elves from both sides, humans, Ogres, and everyone there, on any side of the battle, were falling dead.<br>
<br>
With one last spell, the wizard sent a wave of fire down over the Iksar.  But to no avail.  For each that died, another two seemed to spawn from the corpse.  There seemed no end to the reserves of Iksar within Cabilis.<br>
<br>
Cursing to himself, Undeen began his last spell, the last of his charge with him, encircling him to keep him safe while he prepared their escape.<br>
<br>
With his last words, Ogres, human, elves and Iksar alike swung, only to hit empty air.  Undeen and the last four of his hundred man army, had disappeared from Kunark.  The Iksar had won this battle.  The elves and short race protecting the Firiona Vie docks, would see no such luck.  All the Iksar there that day turned upon them, and the last of the blood was spilt, with the last elf's death.  The Iksar had won this day.  And they celebrated.  They removed heads, and stuck them upon poles and spears.  What had once been an Ogre's arm, could be seen being eaten and tied together with the tendons to make spears.  There were few things stronger then the bones and tendons of an Ogre.  These spears would stab through the strongest of armor.  The Iksar would have their day.  And to that, Undeen and what was left of his forces, could only curse, for if Firiona Vie fell, they knew the Outpost of the OverThere was next...<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Undeen slammed his staff against the top of the pyramid in Nektulos forest as soon as the group appeared, the others cowering away from the noble slightly, &quot;Damn it all!  Those Iksar shall pay for this setback in their disgusting green blood and scales!&quot;  And with that, he was gone, the group walking towards Neriak for shelter and to report what happened.<br>
<br>
The spires in Greater Faydark whirred slightly, and the Wizard appeared, hard eyes looking over the ravished forest.  The elven war had been hell on these woods.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Good.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was all he could think to himself on the subject.<br>
<br>
&quot;I hope these blasted elves slaughter each other so I don't have to waste the energy.&quot; He stepped out further, then heard a cry as a wood elf leaped out of the trees, trying to jump atop him.<br>
<br>
Undeen leapt aside and struck the elf across the head quickly, the energy snapping through the thin elf.  &quot;AHHHH!!!!&quot; was all he could say before he fell to the ground, charred and dead, or dieing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Did you hear that, elves?!  That was the death of another one of you!  You shall ALL feel that death one day!  May it be at my hands!!!&quot;  And with that, he disappeared into the forest, looking for some easy elven game to burn some rage on. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ubellonakali.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bellona Kali</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Child of Hate</span><br>  Posts: 414<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 1:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ffantasystoriesforumfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://auction.2y.net/user/paradisetheheretic/Reineva.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: eq modified rp</span><hr size=1> It was dark. It was always dark in the forest of Nektulous but she never could grow used to it. How many times had she run through these trees? It was as if the sunlight was scared to penetrate the foliage for fear of what it might find. <br>
<br>
“For the Glory of Indigo!”<br>
<br>
Pressed against the trunk of a tree high above the ground was the girl they called Tani. ~Don’t let him see you… Don’t let him see you… Don’t let him see you…~ With eyes squeezed shut she takes in a deep breath and holds it. For a Feir’Dal her skin was quite pale, but after spending most of her time concealed in the shadows, it was expected that her tan would fade. How long was that man going to stay in the same spot? Just as long as he doesn’t look up… Tears form at the corners of her grass green eyes. ~What if he looks up? What if he finds me?~  Clenched tightly in the youths arms was a small bag, it’s contents unidentifiable from the outside. A light breeze rustles the trees and blows a few strands of her butterscotch blonde hair astray. By now she was trembling with fright. She was just a runner; a pawn used by an anti-Teir’Dal group whose whereabouts were virtually unknown. It was a fairly new organization that obviously had no trouble with recruiting adolescences. Slowly opening her right eye, Tani scans the area below her. The guards gone. Breathing a deep sigh of relief, she lets herself rest no longer. Running along branch-to-branch, she makes her way as swiftly and quietly as possible to the rendezvous point. Just as planned, all guards had left their posts at the bridge. Hopping out of the tree, she walks stealthily to the bank. ~In the bushes… off to the right, just at the waters edge… There!~  A tiny hand shakily pulls a straw basket from a thick growth of reeds. Setting the bag within the basket, she pushes it out over the waters surface. Tani’s heart was racing faster than she thought it would be. Leaving a rippling trail behind it, the makeshift boat carries the precious cargo to the opposite bank. <br>
<br>
“ELF! GET HER!”<br>
<br>
Her legs stiffen and she shoots straight up. Guards. Turning around she sees them. Each clad in the same silver armor, with stunningly crafted swords. The stronger guard rushes towards her, his sword held high over her head. Stepping back, she closes her eyes and shields her face with her arms. Home. I want to be home. A rock off sets her balance and her foot slips out from under her. With a thud her butt hits the hard stone surface of the Greater Faydark spires. Thank the Mother! No injuries! Letting out a deep sigh, Tani lays back against the gray pyramid. The treetops part just enough to let sun through and to give a gorgeous view of the vibrant blue sky. Clouds roll by lazily as she gazes upwards. Ah! To be alive still! As she watches a fluffy white bunny shaped one creep by, she can’t help but giggle. Her soft giggles erupt into uncontrollable laughter and she finds herself rolling onto her side. ~I’m alive!!!~<br>
<br>
<br>
